{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"287f6e6a-8b04-432c-814d-2ac9049f3d50","content":"This is a known breaking change in .NET 10. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (API 30), and .NET MAUI 10 enables **edge-to-edge** by default on Android 15+, so the old platform-specific no longer works.\n\nThe fix is to respond to **IME WindowInsets** instead. Here's the approach:\n\n### 1. AndroidManifest.xml — keep `adjustResize`\n\n```xml\n<activity\n    ...\n    android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\">\n```\n\n### 2. Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs — handle IME insets\n\n```csharp\nusing Android.OS;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        var content = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;\n        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new ImeInsetsListener());\n    }\n\n    class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(\n            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n            // Push content up by the keyboard height (minus nav bar)\n            v.SetPadding(\n                bars.Left, 0, bars.Right,\n                System.Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom));\n\n            return insets;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Your XAML layout (chat screen)\n\n```xml\n<Grid RowDefinitions=\"*,Auto\">\n    <CollectionView Grid.Row=\"0\"\n                    ItemsSource=\"{Binding Messages}\"\n                    ItemsUpdatingScrollMode=\"KeepLastItemInView\" />\n\n    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row=\"1\" Padding=\"8\">\n        <Entry Placeholder=\"Type a message...\"\n               HorizontalOptions=\"FillAndExpand\" />\n        <Button Text=\"Send\" Command=\"{Binding SendCommand}\" />\n    </HorizontalStackLayout>\n</Grid>\n```\n\n### Why this works\n\n| .NET 9 | .NET 10 |\n|---|---|\n| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` told Android to shrink the window | Edge-to-edge draws behind system bars; you must read `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` and apply padding yourself |\n\nThe `ImeInsetsListener` fires whenever the keyboard opens or closes, adjusting the bottom padding of the root content view so your input bar slides up above the keyboard.\n\n### iOS\n\nOn iOS this typically works out of the box — MAUI's `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` adjusts for the keyboard. If you still see overlap, you can disable it and handle `UIKeyboard.WillShowNotification` manually, but try the default behavior first.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c3fe7604-2d39-4109-8447-1039c0db2873","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` worked in .NET 9 but doesn't work in .NET 10. This is a known change in .NET MAUI — let me provide guidance based on what I know.\n\nIn .NET MAUI for .NET 9 and earlier, on Android you could use `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` to make the layout resize when the keyboard appeared. However, this API was deprecated in Android 30+ (Android 11+), and .NET MAUI has been moving away from it.\n\n\nIn .NET 10, that approach was removed entirely because Google deprecated the underlying Android API. The modern solution involves using the edge-to-edge model with proper handling of keyboard insets, or configuring `android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\"` directly in the Android manifest if you need the old behavior. but .NET MAUI 10 shifted to using `WindowInsetsCompat` for keyboard handling instead. The practical approach is to set `android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\"` in the manifest while ensuring layouts properly respect window insets, or leverage the newer `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` behavior and `ImeInsets` handling that .NET MAUI introduced for this purpose. For Editor controls specifically, the practical solutions in .NET MAUI 10 are to set `adjustResize` in the manifest, handle edge-to-edge insets by adjusting your layout's bottom padding based on keyboard insets, or wrap content in a `ScrollView` with `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` for automatic scrolling behavior. Setting up window insets listener...\n\nFor a chat app, the most practical approach is ensuring `android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustResize\"` in the manifest, then using platform code to listen for IME insets and adjust the input bar's bottom margin accordingly. In .NET MAUI 10, the older `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated since Android itself moved away from that model, so the replacement strategy depends on whether you're implementing edge-to-edge layouts.\n\nSetting up the Android side involves configuring the manifest and then handling IME insets in the MainActivity to shift content above the keyboard...","outputTokens":2720,"requestId":"D45D:2DE6FB:1C1F444:1FA31A2:6A07BF8D"},"id":"5082f593-657e-499e-b088-8ceec8206987","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:52:13.863Z","parentId":"a98a7cdd-0073-4e6d-b725-4ba527ccf6eb"}
